===Etymology 1===
Late 17th century, unknown origin, possibly {{etyl|cy|en}} {{term|moedrodd|lang=cy}} to worry or bother. Possible alternative from the {{etyl|cy|en}} {{term|meidda||to beg for whey|lang=cy}} or perhaps {{term|meiddio||to dare or venture|lang=cy}}. Bear in mind that the "dd" in Welsh corresponds in sound to the "th" in mither, and English also has [[moider]] and [[moither]].

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|/ˈmaɪθər/}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|mithers|mithering|mithered|mithered}}

# {{context|intransitive|Northern England|lang=en}} To make an [[unnecessary]] [[fuss]], [[moan]], [[bother]].
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[pester]] or [[irritate]] someone. Usually directed at [[children]].
#: ''Will you stop '''mithering''' me!''

